    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-12-29T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-12-29T23:00:00-05:00" n="528"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d528">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12–3045: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Peiping</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stevens</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-12-30T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 30, 1945—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received December 31—4:09
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>“Rumors” of existence in North China of a so-called Japanese National Salvation
                    Organization have reached 11th War Zone Headquarters, Major General Hu
                    Chung-ching, Director of Headquarters’ Foreign Affairs Department, reportedly
                    told press yesterday. He was unable to state the strength of this Japanese
                    underground organization but said its aims are disruption of the existing
                    cordial relations between China and her Allies.</p>
                <p>The spokesman reported that Soviet Russia had [completed?] the withdrawal of her
                    troops from Jehol and that the Chinese had taken over the administration of that
                    province.</p>
                <p>Concerning Communist activity in North China, General Hu reported that “bandit
                    forces” are very active between Kalgan and Huailai and that they are being
                    reinforced in the area west of Nankow. Communists in Hsien [<hi rend="italic"
                        >Sienhsien?</hi>] and Hokien are conscripting tens of thousands of peasants
                    for train wrecking work. The inhabitants of Tsanghsien are being forcibly
                    conscripted and are being sent to other places for military training, the
                    spokesman stated.</p>
                <p>General Hu continued to say that the Communists are beginning to seize winter
                    grain and are forcing the inhabitants to supply them in other ways. (Sent to
                    Chungking; repeated to Department.) He charged that Communists disguised as
                    refugees recently poisoned tea and water in attempts to kill Central Government
                    troops in Hopei Province and that they are organizing bands to assassinate
                    Government soldiers and officials.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>[<hi rend="smallcaps">Stevens</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
